04499nam a22006255i 9780823290925DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232909257 a10.1515/97808232909252doi  a(DE-B1597)566020  a(OCoLC)1306539931  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLAN0270002bisacsh1 aSussman, Henry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAround the Book :bSystems and Literacy /cHenry Sussman. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (352 p.) :b20 Illustrations, black and white  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface: Reaching for the Book -- t1. Introduction: Around the Book -- t2. Extraterrestrial Kafka: Ahead to the Graphic Novel -- t3. Kafka’s Imaginary: A Cognitive Psychology Footnote -- t4. Booking Benjamin: The Fate of a Medium -- t5. Pulsations of Respect, or Winged Impossibility: Poetic Deconstruction -- t6. Hegel, Glas, and the Broader Modernity -- t7. Systems, Games, and the Player: Did We Manage to Become Human? -- t8. Atmospherics of Mood -- t9. Thinking Flat Out: Back to Bateson -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmid radical transformation and rapid mutation in the nature, transmission, and deployment of information and communications, Around the Book offers a status report and theoretically nuanced update on the traditions and medium of the book. What, it asks, are the book’s current prospects? The study highlights the most radical experiments in the book’s history as trials in what the author terms the “Prevailing Operating System” at play within the fields of knowledge, art, critique, and science. The investigations of modern systems theory, as exemplified by Gregory Bateson, Anthony Wilden, and Niklas Luhmann, turn out to be inseparable from theoretically astute inquiry into the nature of the book. Sussman’s primary examples of such radical experiments with the history of the book are Sei Shonagon’s Pillow Book (both the text and Peter Greenaway’s screen adaptation), Stéphane Mallarmé’s “Un coup de dés,” Walter Benjamin’s Arcades Project, Jacques Derrida’s Glas, Maurice Blanchot’s Death Sentence, and Franz Kafka’s enduring legacy within the world of the graphic novel. In the author’s hands, close reading of these and related works renders definitive proof of the book’s persistence and vitality. The book medium, with its inbuilt format and program, continues, he argues, to supply the tablet or screen for cultural notation. The perennial crisis in which the book seems to languish is in fact an occasion for readers to realize fully their role as textual producers, to experience the full range of liberty in expression and articulation embedded in the irreducibly bookish process of textual display.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Publishing.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082323284040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329092540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823290925423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823290925/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LB  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LB  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK